'''Adrián de Moxica''' (1453 &ndash; c. 1499) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[Spanish nobility|nobleman]] and [[Age of Discovery|explorer]].
==Biography== Adrian de Moxica was born to a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] [[Spanish nobility|noble]] family of [[Basque people|Basque]] descent. In 1498 he accompanied [[Christopher Columbus]] on his third journey to the [[Americas]], where he participated in the [[rebellion]] against Columbus in 1499 led by [[Francisco Roldán]]. Moxica had a crucial part in the rebellion and was the main initiator of the atrocities against the Native Americans against the will of Christopher Columbus. Although the rebellion was successful, de Moxica was arrested by Columbus' troops and [[Execution by hanging|hanged]].
==In popular culture== Adrián de Moxica was portrayed by [[Michael Wincott]] in the [[Ridley Scott]]'s [[1992 in film|1992]] film ''[[1492: Conquest of Paradise]]''. Moxica fills a prominent role in the film as Columbus' [[Archenemy|nemesis]], who assumes the role as the leader of Roldán's rebellion with his friend Hernando de Guevara. In the film, Moxica cuts off the hand of a [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] who claimed to have found no gold to pay for his taxes. In reality, it was Columbus who introduced the practice of mutilation as punishment, as discovered in a 2006 report<ref name=newspaper1>{{Cite news |author=[[Giles Tremlett]] |title=Lost document reveals Columbus as tyrant of the Caribbean |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/aug/07/books.spain |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=7 August 2006 |accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>. This contrasts with the benevolent Columbus portrayed in the movie.
