[[Image:Mapa Geografico de America Meridional (acercamiento).jpg|thumb|right|[[Patagonia]] map by Juan de la Cruz, 1775]]

'''Juan de la Cruz Cano y Olmedilla''' was a Spanish  [[cartographer]]. For many years, Cano was the cartographer of the king [[Charles III of Spain|Carlos III]] of Spain.

He made maps of [[Spain]] and of the Spanish possessions in [[Latin America]].<ref name=wca>[http://www.worldcat.org/search?qt=worldcat_org_all&q=Juan%20de%20la%20Cruz%20Cano%20y%20Olmedilla   WorldCat author listing]</ref> He is especially known for a 1775 map of South America.<ref>Ristow, Walter W, and Cano O. J. Cruz. ''The Juan De La Cruz Map of South America, 1775.'' Evanston, Ill, 1962 in "Festschrift: Clarence F. Jones," ed. by Merle C. Prunty, Jr. Northwestern University Studies in Geography, no. 6, 1962. OCLC 39063331</ref><ref>Smith, Thomas R. The Juan De La Cruz Cano Map of South America, 1771-1775; the Internal Evidence of Its States and Publications. S.l, n.d..  OCLC 84373402</ref><ref>Vázquez, de A. I. Don Juan De La Cruz, Su Mapa De América Meridional (1775) Y Las Fronteras Del Reino De Chile. Santiago: Instituto de Investigaciones del Patrimonio Territorial de Chile, Universidad de Santiago, 1984 OCLC 15695566</ref><ref>Bornholt, Jens P, William H. Hempstead, Philippe Vandermaelen, and Cano O. J. Cruz. Cuatro Siglos De Expresiones Geográficas Del Istmo Centroamericano, 1500-1900  / Four Centuries of Geographic Expressions of the Central American Isthmus. Guatemala: Universidad Francisco Morroquín, 2007. OCLC 190861309;  {{ISBN|9789992279953}}</ref>

